Ray will release CPU resources when being blocked. This prevents deadlock cases where the nested tasks are waiting for the CPU resources held by the parent task. Consider the following remote function.
```
@ray.remote(num_cpus=1, num_gpus=1)
def g():
    return ray.get(f.remote())

```
When a `g` task is executing, it will release its CPU resources when it gets blocked in the call to `ray.get`. It will reacquire the CPU resources when `ray.get` returns. It will retain its GPU resources throughout the lifetime of the task because the task will most likely continue to use GPU memory. 解释下这是啥意思
